# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sass-scss
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] CSS is designed to enable the separation of content and presentation, including layout, colors, and fonts.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] Separation of formatting and content also makes it feasible to present the same markup page in different styles for different rendering methods, such as on-screen, in print, by voice (via speech-based browser or screen reader), and on Braille-based tactile devices.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] CSS also has rules for alternative formatting if the content is accessed on a mobile device.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] The name *cascading* comes from the specified priority scheme to determine which declaration applies if more than one declaration of a property match a particular element.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] This cascading priority scheme is predictable.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] The CSS specifications are maintained by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] Internet media type (MIME type) `text/css` is registered for use with CSS by RFC 2318 (March 1998).
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] The W3C operates a free CSS validation service for CSS documents.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] In addition to HTML, other markup languages support the use of CSS including XHTML, plain XML, SVG, and XUL.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] CSS is also used in the GTK widget toolkit.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] CSS has a simple syntax and uses a number of English keywords to specify the names of various style properties.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] A style sheet consists of a list of *rules*.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] Each rule or rule-set consists of one or more *selectors*, and a *declaration block*.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] In CSS, *selectors* declare which part of the markup a style applies to by matching tags and attributes in the markup itself.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] Classes and IDs are case-sensitive, start with letters, and can include alphanumeric characters, hyphens, and underscores.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] A class may apply to any number of instances of any element.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] An ID may only be applied to a single element.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] One example of a widely used pseudo-class is `:hover`, which identifies content only when the user "points to" the visible element, usually by holding the mouse cursor over it.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] It is appended to a selector as in `a:hover` or `#elementid:hover`.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] A pseudo-class classifies document elements, such as `:link` or `:visited`, whereas a *pseudo-element* makes a selection that may consist of partial elements, such as `::first-line` or `::first-letter`.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] Note the distinction between the double-colon notation used for pseudo-elements and the single-colon notation used for pseudo-classes.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] Multiple simple selectors may be joined using combinators to specify elements by location, element type, id, class, or any combination thereof.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] The order of the selectors is important.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] For example, `div .myClass {color: red;}` applies to all elements of class myClass that are inside div elements, whereas `.myClass div {color: red;}` applies to all div elements that are inside elements of class myClass.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] This is not to be confused with concatenated identifiers such as `div.myClass {color: red;}` which applies to div elements of class myClass.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] The following table provides a summary of selector syntax indicating usage and the version of CSS that introduced it.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] A declaration block consists of a pair of braces (`{}`) enclosing a semicolon-separated list of *declarations*.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] Each declaration itself consists of a *property*, a colon (`:`), and a *value*.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] Optional white-space may be around the declaration block, declarations, colons, and semi-colons for readability.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] Properties are specified in the CSS standard.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] Each property has a set of possible values.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] Some properties can affect any type of element, and others apply only to particular groups of elements.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] Values may be keywords, such as "center" or "inherit", or numerical values, such as `200px` (200 pixels), `50vw` (50 percent of the viewport width) or 80% (80 percent of the parent element's width).
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] Color values can be specified with keywords (e.g.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] `rgb(255, 0, 0)`), RGBA values that specify both color and alpha transparency (e.g.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] Non-zero numeric values representing linear measures must include a length unit, which is either an alphabetic code or abbreviation, as in `200px` or `50vw`; or a percentage sign, as in `80%`.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] These eight units were a feature of CSS 1 and retained in all subsequent revisions.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] The proposed CSS Values and Units Module Level 3 will, if adopted as a W3C Recommendation, provide seven further length units: `ch`; `Q`; `rem`; `vh`; `vmax`; `vmin`; and `vw`.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] Before CSS, nearly all presentational attributes of HTML documents were contained within the HTML markup.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] That is, all font colors, background styles, element alignments, borders, and sizes had to be explicitly described (often repeatedly) within the HTML.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] CSS lets authors move much of that information to another file, the style sheet, resulting in considerably simpler HTML.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] And additionally, as more and more devices are able to access responsive web pages, different screen sizes and layouts begin to appear.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] Customizing a website for each device size is costly and increasingly difficult.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] The modular nature of CSS means that styles can be reused in different parts of a site or even across sites, promoting consistency and efficiency.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] For example, headings (`h1` elements), sub-headings (`h2`), sub-sub-headings (`h3`), etc., are defined structurally using HTML.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] In print and on the screen, choice of font, size, color and emphasis for these elements is *presentational*.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] Before CSS, document authors who wanted to assign such typographic characteristics to, say, all `h2` headings had to repeat HTML presentational markup for each occurrence of that heading type.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] This made documents more complex, larger, and more error-prone and difficult to maintain.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] CSS allows the separation of presentation from structure.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] CSS can define color, font, text alignment, size, borders, spacing, layout and many other typographic characteristics, and can do so independently for on-screen and printed views.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] CSS also defines non-visual styles, such as reading speed and emphasis for aural text readers.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] The W3C has now deprecated the use of all presentational HTML markup.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] The advantages of this may not be immediately clear but the power of CSS becomes more apparent when the style properties are placed in an internal style element or, even better, an external CSS file.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] All `h1` elements in the document will then automatically become red without requiring any explicit code.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] rather than by laboriously going through the document and changing the color for each individual `h1` element.
[src:sass-scss/cascading-style-sheets] This further decouples the styling from the HTML document and makes it possible to restyle multiple documents by simply editing a shared external CSS file.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Specificity is the weight that is applied to a given CSS declaration.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The specificity algorithm calculates that weight based on the number of selectors of each weight category in the selector matching the element (or pseudo-element).
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] If there are two or more declarations providing different property values for the same element, the declaration value in the style block having the matching selector with the greatest weight gets applied.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The specificity value is basically a three-column value of three categories or weights - ID, CLASS, and TYPE - corresponding to the three types of selectors.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The value represents the count of selector components in each weight category and is written as *ID - CLASS - TYPE*.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The three columns are created by counting the number of selector components for each selector weight category in the selectors that match the element.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Includes only ID selectors, such as `#example`.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] For each ID in a matching selector, add 1-0-0 to the weight value.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Includes class selectors, such as `.myClass`, attribute selectors like `[type="radio"]` and `[lang|="fr"]`, and pseudo-classes, such as `:hover`, `:nth-of-type(3n)`, and `:required`.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] For each class, attribute selector, or pseudo-class in a matching selector, add 0-1-0 to the weight value.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Includes type selectors, such as `p`, `h1`, and `td`, and pseudo-elements like `::before`, `::placeholder`, and all other selectors with double-colon notation.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] For each type or pseudo-element in a matching selector, add 0-0-1 to the weight value.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The universal selector (`*`) and the pseudo-class `:where()` and its parameters aren't counted when calculating the weight so their value is 0-0-0, but they do match elements.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] These selectors do not impact the specificity weight value.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Combinators, such as `+`, `>`, `~`, " ", and `||`, may make a selector more specific in what is selected but they don't add any value to the specificity weight.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The `&` nesting combinator doesn't add specificity weight, but nested rules do.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] In terms of specificity, and functionality, nesting is very similar to the `:is()` pseudo-class.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Like nesting, the `:is()`, `:has()`, and negation (`:not()`) pseudo-classes themselves add no weight.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The parameters in these selectors, however, do.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The specificity weight of each comes from the selector parameter in the list of selectors with the highest specificity.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Similarly, with nested selectors, the specificity weight added by the nested selector component is the selector in the comma-separated list of nested selectors with the highest specificity.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The `:not()`, `:is()`, `:has()` and CSS nesting exceptions are discussed below.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The specificity weight comes from the matching selector.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The `[type="password"]` selector in the above selector list, with a specificity weight of `0-1-0`, applies the `color: blue` declaration to all password input types.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] All inputs, no matter the type, when receiving focus, match the second selector in the list, `input:focus`, with a specificity weight of `0-1-1`; this weight is made up of the `:focus` pseudo-class (0-1-0) and the `input` type (0-0-1).
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] If the password input has focus, it will match `input:focus`, and the specificity weight for the `color: blue` style declaration will be `0-1-1`.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] When that password doesn't have focus, the specificity weight remains at `0-1-0`.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The specificity for a required input nested in an element with attribute `id="myApp"` is `1-2-1`, based on one ID, two pseudo-classes, and one element type.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] If the password input type with `required` is nested in an element with `id="myApp"` set, the specificity weight will be `1-2-1`, based on one ID, two pseudo-classes, and one element type, whether or not it has focus.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Why is the specificity weight `1-2-1` rather than `0-1-1` or `0-1-0` in this case?
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Because the specificity weight comes from the matching selector with the greatest specificity weight.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The weight is determined by comparing the values in the three columns, from left to right.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Once the specificity values of the relevant selectors are determined, the number of selector components in each column are compared, from left to right.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The first column is the value of the *ID* component, which is the number of IDs in each selector.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The numbers in the *ID* columns of competing selectors are compared.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The selector with the greater value in the *ID* column wins no matter what the values are in the other columns.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] In the above example, even though the yellow selector has more components in total, only the value of the first column matters.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] If the number in the *ID* columns of competing selectors is the same, then the next column, *CLASS*, is compared, as shown below.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The *CLASS* column is the count of class names, attribute selectors, and pseudo-classes in the selector.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] When the *ID* column value is the same, the selector with the greater value in the *CLASS* column wins, no matter the value in the *TYPE* column.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] If the numbers in the *CLASS* and *ID* columns in competing selectors are the same, the *TYPE* column becomes relevant.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The *TYPE* column is the number of element types and pseudo-elements in the selector.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] When the first two columns have the same value, the selector with the greater number in the *TYPE* column wins.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] If the competing selectors have the same values in all the three columns, the proximity rule comes into play, wherein the last declared style gets precedence.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The matches-any pseudo-class `:is()`, the relational pseudo-class `:has()`, and the negation pseudo-class `:not()` are *not* considered as pseudo-classes in the specificity weight calculation.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] They themselves don't add any weight to the specificity equation.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] However, the selector parameters passed into the pseudo-class parenthesis are part of the specificity algorithm; the weight of the matches-any and negation pseudo-class in the specificity value calculation is the weight of the parameter's weight.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Note that in the above CSS pairing, the specificity weight provided by the `:is()`, `:has()` and `:not()` pseudo-classes is the value of the selector parameter, not of the pseudo-class.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] All three of these pseudo-classes accept complex selector lists, a list of comma-separated selectors, as a parameter.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] In the above CSS code block, we have included `#fakeId` in the selectors.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] This `#fakeId` adds `1-0-0` to the specificity weight of each paragraph.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] When creating complex selector lists with CSS nesting this behaves in exactly the same way as the `:is()` pseudo-class.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] In the above code block the complex selector `p, #fakeId` the specificity is taken from `#fakeId` and also the `span`, so this create a specificity of `1-0-1` for both `p span` and `#fakeId span`.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] This is the equivalent specificity as the `:is(p, #fakeId) span` selector.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Generally, you want to keep specificity down to a minimum, but if you need to increase an element's specificity for a particular reason, these three pseudo-classes can help.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] In this example, all links will be blue, unless overridden by a link declaration with 3 or more IDs, a color value matching an `a` includes the `!important` flag, or if the link has an inline style color declaration.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] If you use such a technique, add a comment to explain why the hack was needed.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Inline styles added to an element (e.g., `style="font-weight: bold;"`) always overwrite any normal styles in author stylesheets, and therefore, can be thought of as having the highest specificity.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Think of inline styles as having a specificity weight of `1-0-0-0`.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The only way to override inline styles is by using `!important`.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Many JavaScript frameworks and libraries add inline styles.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Using `!important` with a very targeted selector, such as an attribute selector using the inline style, is one way to override these inline styles.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Make sure to include a comment with every inclusion of the important flag so code maintainers understand why a CSS anti-pattern was used.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] CSS declarations marked as important override any other declarations within the same cascade layer and origin.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Although technically, `!important` has nothing to do with specificity, it interacts directly with specificity and the cascade.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] It reverses the cascade order of stylesheets.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] If declarations from the same origin and cascade layer conflict and one property value has the `!important` flag set, the important declaration is applied no matter the specificity.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] When conflicting declarations from the same origin and cascade layer with the `!important` flag are applied to the same element, the declaration with a greater specificity is applied.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Using `!important` to override specificity is considered a **bad practice** and should be avoided for this purpose.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Understanding and effectively using specificity and the cascade can remove any need for the `!important` flag.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Instead of using `!important` to override foreign CSS (from external libraries, like Bootstrap or normalize.css), import the third-party scripts directly into cascade layers.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] If you must use `!important` in your CSS, comment your usage so future code maintainers know why the declaration was marked important and know not to override it.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] But definitely, don't use `!important` when writing plugins or frameworks that other developers will need to incorporate without being able to control.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The specificity-adjustment pseudo-class `:where()` always has its specificity replaced with zero, `0-0-0`.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] It enables making CSS selectors very specific in what element is targeted without any increase to specificity.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] In creating third-party CSS to be used by developers who don't have access to edit your CSS, it's considered a good practice to create CSS with the lowest possible specificity.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Then the developer implementing the widget can easily override the link color using only type selectors.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Including a ruleset inside a `@scope` block does not affect the specificity of its selector, regardless of the selectors used inside the scope root and limit.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] However, if you decide to explicitly add the `:scope` pseudo-class, you'll need to factor it in when calculating their specificity.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] `:scope`, like all regular pseudo-classes, has a specificity of 0-1-0.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] See Specificity in `@scope` for more information.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Instead of using `!important`, consider using cascade layers and using low weight specificity throughout your CSS so that styles are easily overridden with slightly more specific rules.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Using semantic HTML helps provide anchors from which to apply styling.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] By indicating the section of the document you're styling before the element you're selecting, the rule becomes more specific.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] No matter the order, the heading will be green because that rule is the most specific.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Specificity is based on the form of a selector.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Including the `id` of an element as an attribute selector rather than an id selector is a good way to make an element more specific without adding an overabundance of specificity.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] In the previous example, the selector `[id="myContent"]` counts as an attribute selector for the purpose of determining the selector's specificity, even though it selects an ID.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] You can also include the `id` or any part of a selector as a parameter in the `:where()` specificity-adjustment pseudo class if you need to make a selector more specific but don't want to add any specificity at all.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] As a special case for increasing specificity, you can duplicate weights from the *CLASS* or *ID* columns.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Duplicating id, class, pseudo-class or attribute selectors within a compound selector will increase specificity when overriding very specific selectors over which you have no control.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] If using selector duplication, always comment your CSS.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Leveraging cascade layers is the standard way of enabling one set of styles to take precedence over another set of styles; cascade layers enable this without using specificity!
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Normal (not important) author styles imported into cascade layers have lower precedence than unlayered author styles.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] If styles are coming from a stylesheet you can't edit or don't understand and you need to override styles, a strategy is to import the styles you don't control into a cascade layer.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Styles in subsequently declared layers take precedence, with unlayered styles having precedence over all layered styles from the same origin.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] When two selectors from different layers match the same element, origin and importance take precedence; the specificity of the selector in the losing stylesheet is irrelevant.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] In the above example, all paragraph text, including the nested content, will be `1rem` no matter how many class names the paragraphs have that match the TW stylesheet.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The best approach is to not use `!important`.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The above explanations on specificity should be helpful in avoiding using the flag and removing it altogether when encountered.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] All these methods are covered in preceding sections.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] If you're unable to remove `!important` flags from an authors style sheet, the only solution to overriding the important styles is by using `!important`.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Creating a cascade layer of important declaration overrides is an excellent solution.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Import this stylesheet as the first import in your CSS using `layer()`, including the `@import` statement, before linking to other stylesheets.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] This is to ensure that the important overrides is imported as the first layer.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Each time you need to override an important declaration, declare it within the named layer.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Only declare important rules within the layer.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The specificity of the selector of the important style within the layer can be low, as long as it matches the element you are trying to override.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Normal layers should be declared outside the layer because layered styles have lower precedence than unlayered styles.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The proximity of an element to other elements that are referenced in a given selector has no impact on specificity.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The `<h1>` elements will be purple because when declarations have the same specificity, the last declared selector has precedence.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Styles for a directly targeted element will always take precedence over inherited styles, regardless of the specificity of the inherited rule.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The `h1` will be purple because the `h1` selector targets the element specifically, while the green is inherited from the `#parent` declarations.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] In the following CSS, we have three selectors targeting `<input>` elements to set a color.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] If the above selectors all target the same input, the input will be red, as the first declaration has the highest value in the *ID* column.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The last selector has four *TYPE* components.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] While it has the highest integer value, no matter how many elements and pseudo-elements are included, even if there were 150, TYPE components never have precedence over *CLASS* components.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] The column values are compared starting from left to right when column values are equal.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] When multiple declarations have equal specificity, the last declaration found in the CSS is applied to the element.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] If both selectors match the same `<input>`, the color will be blue.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] When two selectors in the same cascade layer and origin have the same specificity, scoping proximity is then calculated; the ruleset with the lowest scoping proximity wins.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] See How `@scope` conflicts are resolved for more details and an example.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] If scope proximity is also the same for both selectors, source order then comes into play.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] When all else is equal, the last selector wins.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] As per CSS rules, directly targeted elements will always take precedence over rules which an element inherits from its ancestor.
[src:sass-scss/css-cascade-specificity] Proximity of elements in the document tree has no effect on the specificity.
[src:sass-scss/css-css-nesting] The **CSS nesting** module defines a syntax for nesting selectors, providing the ability to nest one style rule inside another, with the selector of the child rule relative to the selector of the parent rule.
[src:sass-scss/css-css-nesting] CSS nesting is different from CSS preprocessors such as Sass in that it is parsed by the browser rather than being pre-compiled by a CSS preprocessor.
[src:sass-scss/css-css-nesting] CSS nesting helps with the readability, modularity, and maintainability of CSS stylesheets.
[src:sass-scss/css-css-nesting] It also potentially helps reduce the size of CSS files, thereby decreasing the amount of data downloaded by users.
[src:sass-scss/css-css-nesting] Explains the differences in specificity when nesting CSS.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] The basic goal of the Cascading Stylesheet (CSS) language is to allow a browser engine to paint elements of the page with specific features, like colors, positioning, or decorations.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] Setting CSS properties to specific values is the core function of the CSS language.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] A property and value pair is called a **declaration**, and any CSS engine calculates which declarations apply to every single element of a page in order to appropriately lay it out, and to style it.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] Both properties and values are case-insensitive by default in CSS.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] The pair is separated by a colon, `:` (U+003A COLON), and white spaces before, between, and after properties and values, but not necessarily inside, are ignored.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] There are hundreds of different properties in CSS and a practically endless number of different values.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] Not all pairs of properties and values are allowed and each property defines what are the valid values.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] When a value is not valid for a given property, the declaration is deemed *invalid* and is wholly ignored by the CSS engine.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] Declarations are grouped in **blocks**, that is in a structure delimited by an opening brace, `{` (U+007B LEFT CURLY BRACKET), and a closing one, `}` (U+007D RIGHT CURLY BRACKET).
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] Blocks sometimes can be nested, so opening and closing braces must be matched.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] Such blocks are naturally called **declaration blocks** and declarations inside them are separated by a semicolon, `;` (U+003B SEMICOLON).
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] A declaration block may be empty, that is containing null declaration.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] White spaces around declarations are ignored.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] The last declaration of a block doesn't need to be terminated by a semicolon, though it is often considered *good style* to do it as it prevents forgetting to add it when extending the block with another declaration.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] A CSS declaration block is visualized in the diagram below.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] If style sheets could only apply a declaration to each element of a Web page, they would be pretty useless.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] The real goal is to apply different declarations to different parts of the document.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] CSS allows this by associating conditions with declarations blocks.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] Each (valid) declaration block is preceded by one or more comma-separated **selectors**, which are conditions selecting some elements of the page.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] A selector list and an associated declarations block, together, are called a **ruleset**, or often a **rule**.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] A CSS ruleset (or rule) is visualized in the diagram below.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] This leads to an important consequence: if one single basic selector is invalid, like when using an unknown pseudo-element or pseudo-class, the whole *selector* is invalid and therefore the entire rule is ignored (as invalid too).
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] Rulesets are the main building blocks of a style sheet, which often consists of only a big list of them.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] But there is other information that a Web author wants to convey in the style sheet, like the character set, other external style sheets to import, font face or list counter descriptions and many more.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] It will use other and specific kinds of statements to do that.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] A **statement** is a building block that begins with any non-space characters and ends at the first closing brace or semicolon (outside a string, non-escaped and not included into another {}, () or [] pair).
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] (A Venn diagram of statements noting all rulesets are nested statements, while some at-rules are nested statements but most aren't.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] Any statement which isn't a ruleset or an at-rule is invalid and ignored.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] There is another group of statements – the **nested statements**.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] These are statements that can be used in a specific subset of at-rules – the *conditional group rules*.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] These statements only apply if a specific condition is matched: the `@media` at-rule content is applied only if the device on which the browser runs matches the expressed condition; the `@document` at-rule content is applied only if the current page matches some conditions, and so on.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] In CSS1 and CSS2.1, only *rulesets* could be used inside conditional group rules.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] That was very restrictive and this restriction was lifted in *CSS Conditionals Level 3*.
[src:sass-scss/css-syntax] Now, though still experimental and not supported by every browser, conditional group rules can contain a wider range of content: rulesets but also some, but not all, at-rules.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] The original syntax, called "the indented syntax," uses a syntax similar to Haml.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] It uses indentation to separate code blocks and newline characters to separate rules.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] The newer syntax, **SCSS** (Sassy CSS), uses block formatting like that of CSS.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] It uses braces to denote code blocks and semicolons to separate rules within a block.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] The indented syntax and SCSS files are traditionally given the extensions .sass and .scss, respectively.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] CSS3 consists of a series of selectors and pseudo-selectors that group rules that apply to them.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] Sass (in the larger context of both syntaxes) extends CSS by providing several mechanisms available in more traditional programming languages, particularly object-oriented languages, but that are not available to CSS3 itself.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] When SassScript is interpreted, it creates blocks of CSS rules for various selectors as defined by the Sass file.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] The Sass interpreter translates SassScript into CSS.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] Alternatively, Sass can monitor the .sass or .scss file and translate it to an output .css file whenever the .sass or .scss file is saved.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] SCSS is a nested metalanguage and a superset of CSS, as valid CSS is valid SCSS with the same semantics.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] SassScript provides the following mechanisms: variables, nesting, mixins, and selector inheritance.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] Sass was initially designed by Hampton Catlin and developed by Natalie Weizenbaum.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] Variables begin with a dollar sign (`$`).
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] Variable assignment is done with a colon (`:`).
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] Variables can be arguments to or results from one of several available functions.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] During translation, the values of the variables are inserted into the output CSS document.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] CSS does support logical nesting, but the code blocks themselves are not nested.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] Sass allows the nested code to be inserted within each other.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] More complicated types of nesting including namespace nesting and parent references are discussed in the Sass documentation.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] Sass allows for iterating over variables using `@for`, `@each` and `@while`, which can be used to apply different styles to elements with similar classes or ids.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] While CSS3 supports the Document Object Model (DOM) hierarchy, it does not allow selector inheritance.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] In Sass, inheritance is achieved by inserting a line inside of a code block that uses the @extend keyword and references another selector.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] The extended selector's attributes are applied to the calling selector.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] At the 2012 HTML5 Developer Conference, Hampton Catlin, the creator of Sass, announced version 1.0 of libSass, an open source C++ implementation of Sass developed by Catlin, Aaron Leung, and the engineering team at Moovweb.
[src:sass-scss/sass-style-sheet-language] According to Catlin, libSass can be "drop[ped] into anything and it will have Sass in it...You could drop it right into Firefox today and build Firefox and it will compile in there.
